 a baker in Amman, Martínez probes the practices that underpin subsidized bread. Following bakers and bureaucrats, he offers an immersive examination of social welfare provision. Martínez argues that the state is best understood as the product of routine practices and actions, through which it becomes a stable truth in the lives of citizens. States of Subsistence not only describes logics of rule in contemporary Jordan—and the place of bread within them—but also unpacks how the state endures through forms, sensations, and practices amid the seemingly unglamorous and unspectacular day-to-day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBread industryxPolitical aspectszJordan. 0aBread industryxSubsidieszJordan. 0aBreadxGovernment policyzJordan. 0aPublic welfarezJordan. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aJordan.  abread.  acraft.  aeveryday.  afood politics.  aperformativity.  asensation.  astate.  awelfare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363133540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631335/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles